	[SQL Injection Bypassing WAF.docx]
		Web applications are frequently targeted by threat actors due to their rapid production and wide attack surface. A recent security audit from Astra Security [1] states that a web application faces a cyber-attack every 39 s. The surge in web applications and smartphone usage, coupled with the increasing technical proficiency of end users, has led to a spike in web traffic. Businesses migrating their systems from offline to online systems has provided threat actors with an increased attack surface to exploit. The Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) lists SQL Injection (SQLi) among the top three web application security risks in both the 2017 and 2021 versions [2]. An SQLi attack is a web attack that is used to target data stored in database management systems (DBMS) by injecting malicious input, which is directly concatenated with original SQL queries issued by the client application to subvert application functionality and perform unauthorized operations
